{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":27908,"duration_api_ms":27884,"num_turns":2,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"68119d3f-4b67-4a4b-8dd6-bdb26fee2ff2","total_cost_usd":0.187225,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":21504,"cache_read_input_tokens":43420,"output_tokens":1244,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":21504,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":3,"outputTokens":1244,"cacheReadInputTokens":43420,"cacheCreationInputTokens":21504,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.187225,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All four amendments identify real, well-reasoned defects. The dual-timeout race makes artifact preservation dead code; the test gap fails to catch it; the non-Unix kill path leaks processes; and exit-127 misclassification creates false non-retryable failures. Each amendment provides clear technical reasoning and actionable fixes.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-3-a95af876","decision":"accept","rationale":"The dual-timeout race is a genuine bug. Both layers use request.timeout but the service-layer timeout wraps the entire invoke() including build_command() and spawn() overhead, so it fires first. This makes the inner timeout's preserve_failed_artifacts call at lines 1193-1196 unreachable in production, silently losing diagnostic artifacts on timeout. Both proposed fixes (buffering the outer timeout or moving preservation to the cancel/cleanup path) are sound."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-e384feeb","decision":"accept","rationale":"The test only asserts the return type (FailureClass::Timeout) without verifying the critical side effect: artifact preservation to runtime/failed. This is a meaningful coverage gap. The artifact preservation path is currently unreachable (per fr-3-a95af876), and this test would not detect that regression. Asserting the existence of .failed.raw and Codex-specific files after timeout provides proper behavioral verification."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-1c23f8ce","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a confirmed process leak on non-Unix platforms. send_sigkill() returns Err(Unsupported) under #[cfg(not(unix))], the error is silently discarded via `let _`, child.wait() then blocks indefinitely since the process was never terminated, and the Arc<ManagedChild> held by the background task prevents kill_on_drop from ever firing. The timeout returns to the caller while the backend process runs indefinitely, violating the hard-timeout guarantee."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-ccb079f3","decision":"accept","rationale":"Exit code 127 post-spawn is application-defined, not proof of a missing binary. Missing executables are already caught by resolve_binary() (BackendUnavailable) and command.spawn() (ErrorKind::NotFound → BinaryNotFound). Once the process has spawned and executed, 127 is just a conventional exit code that shells and wrapper scripts use for their own error semantics. Unconditionally mapping it to non-retryable BinaryNotFound bypasses the retry budget for potentially transient or recoverable errors, and should be treated as TransportFailure like other non-zero exits."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"08ec128a-3580-4267-953b-0c1a7f43b1f2"}
